Question 1: Simple Linear Regression

We are going to work with the dataset bike_data.csv (provided in Files->Assignments->Assignment_3). This dataset has been dowloaded from Kaggle, which is an online prediction contest website (see https://www.kaggle.com/c/bike-sharing-demand/data). The data is essentially the log of hourly bike rentals in a city over two years. The following is the codebook:

. datetime - hourly date + timestamp
. season - 1 = spring, 2 = summer, 3 = fall, 4 = winter
. holiday - whether the day is considered a holiday
. workingday - whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday
. weather - 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy , 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist , 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds , 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog
. temp - temperature in Celsius
. atemp - feels like temperature in Celsius
. humidity - relative humidity
. windspeed - wind speed . . casual - number of non-registered user rentals initiated
. registered - number of registered user rentals initiated
. count - number of total rentals

First, we need to do some preprocessing. Specifically, we need to process the year variable and remove all observations with weather == 4 (these are outliers and need to be be removed).

# set up
rm(list=ls())
library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)

# Read the dataset in
bike_data <- read.csv("bike_data.csv", header = TRUE)

# Preprocess
bike_data <- bike_data %>% mutate(datetime_f = mdy_hm(datetime)) %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(year(datetime_f))) %>%
  mutate(weather = as.factor(weather)) %>%
  filter(weather != "4")

  1. how does each variable contribute to count in terms of increase or decrease? ### can delete this later Ans.

Temp (continous): Holding all other variables constant, an increase in 1 degree Celsius is correlated with an increase of 10 bike rentals. (p-value < 0.001)

Season (categorical): Holding all other variables constant - In season 2(summer): The average number of bike rentals increases by 4. (p-value = 0.37) - In season 3(fall): The average number of bike rentals decreases by 29. (p-value < 0.001) - In season 4(winter): The average number of bike rentals increase by 67. (p-value < 0.001)

Humidity (continous): Holding all other variables constant, an increase in 1 unit of humidity is correlated with an average decrease of 2 bike rentals. (p-value < 0.001)

Weather (categorical): Holding all other variables constant - In weather 2(Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist): The average number of bike rentals increases by 11. (p-value < 0.001) - In weather 3(Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds): The average number of bike rentals decreases by 7. (p-value = 0.2)

Year (continous): Holding all other variables constant, an increase in 1 year (2011-2012) is correlated with an increase of 75 bike rentals. (p-value < 0.001)

  1. what can you say about the results and the quality of fit? Use pvalue threshold of < 0.001 to reject any null hypothesis.
    Ans. Ho = There is no significance between bike rentals vs.temperature, season, humidity, weather, and year. Ha = There is a significance between bike rentals vs.temperature, season, humidity, weather, and year.

If the p-value < 0.001; reject the null hypothesis (Ho) and accept the alternate hypothesis (Ha). If the p-value > 0.001; there is insufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis (Ho). In addition, a R2 value of 0.32 indicates a good quality of fit.

Question 3: Multiple Linear Regression - II

This question deals within application of linear regression. Download the dataset titled sales_advertising.csv from Files -> Assignments -> Assignment_3. The dataset measure sales of a product as a function of advertising budgets for TV, radio, and newspaper media. The following is the data dictionary.

  1. TV: advertising budget for TV (in thousands of dollars)
  2. radio: advertising budget for radio (in thousands of dollars)
  3. newspaper: advertising budget for newspaper (in thousands of dollars)
  4. sales: sales of product (in thousands of units)
  1. Plot the response (sales) against all three predictors in three separate plots. Write your code below. Do any of the plots show a linear trend?

  1. What are the observed associations between sales and each of the media budgets? Mention which associations are significant. Use a p-value threshold of <0.05 to indicate significance.
    Ans.

o = 2.94, TV = 0.0458, Radio = 0.19, Newspaper = -0.001

TV: Holding all other variables constant, an increase by $1000 spent on the TV advertising budget is correlated with an increase of 46 units in sales. Since p-value < 0.05, this association is statistically significant.

Radio: Holding all other variables constant, an increase by $1000 spent on the Radio advertising budget is correlated with an increase of 189 units in sales. Since p-value < 0.05, this association is stastically significant.

Newspaper: Holding all other variables constant, an increase by $1000 spent on the Newspaper advertising budget is correlated with a decrease of 1 unit in sales. (p-value = 0.86) Since p-value > 0.05, this association is not stastically significant.

  1. Do you observe any difference in the associations in the multiple regression model vs.the simple regression model? Explain why or why not.
    Ans.

In the simple regression model for TV, Radio, and Newspaper, the 1 values (slope) were 0.05, 0.2, and 0.05. In the multiple regression model, the slopes were 0.05, 0.2, and -0.001. The Newspaper slope value in the multiple regression model was not signifiant (p-value = 0.86). Therefore, as individual predictors (TV, Radio, Newspaper), their relationship with the response (sales) is significant. When the Newspaper predictor interacts with the other individuals predictors (TV and Radio), the relationship is not stastically significant.
